00:13:23,500 --> 00:13:28,500
and the new head does not care about barium whatsoever. The new head is barium adapted. That's kind of amazing.

76
00:13:28,500 --> 00:13:34,500
We asked a simple question. We just looked at the transcriptomes of naive worms versus barium adapted heads,

77
00:13:34,500 --> 00:13:39,500
and we just asked, well, what gene expression is different? What's different about these barium adapted heads?

78
00:13:39,500 --> 00:13:45,500
One thing we found is that there's only a handful of genes. There's less than a dozen genes that are in fact different,

79
00:13:45,500 --> 00:13:54,500
and so this system is able to figure out which genes to up and down regulate so that it can do its business without being able to pass potassium properly.

80
00:13:54,500 --> 00:13:59,500
But the incredible thing about this is that barium is not anything that planaria ever see in the wild.

81
00:13:59,500 --> 00:14:09,500
This is a completely unnatural novel stressor. So it's implausible to think that at some point there was evolutionary pressure to develop a response to barium.

82
00:14:09,500 --> 00:14:16,500
