And so I think the reason that we are still roughly where computer science was in the 50s

160
00:21:07,500 --> 00:21:11,500
is because we've been neglecting one important aspect.

161
00:21:11,500 --> 00:21:14,500
And that is multi-scale intelligence and biology.

162
00:21:14,500 --> 00:21:16,500
Now, what do I mean by intelligence?

163
00:21:16,500 --> 00:21:22,500
I mean what William James meant, which is the ability to reach the same goal by different means.

164
00:21:22,500 --> 00:21:28,500
And when we talk about pattern and anatomy, when I talk about goals, I mean regions of morphospace.

165
00:21:28,500 --> 00:21:29,500
Now, what's morphospace?

166
00:21:29,500 --> 00:21:36,500
Morphospace is the space of all possible configurations of some particular structure.

167
00:21:36,500 --> 00:21:40,500
So if you're looking at snail shells, for example, there are three parameters that you can define.

168
00:21:40,500 --> 00:21:47,500
And every shell is, every possible snail shell is some point within this morphospace.

169
00:21:47,500 --> 00:21:50,500
And this is an idea that's very old.

170
00:21:50,500 --> 00:21:56,500
In fact, Darcy Thompson in the 40s had this interesting example in his book on growth and form,

171
00:21:56,500 --> 00:22:00,500
where he noticed that if you just deform certain animal shapes placed on a grid,

172
00:22:00,500 --> 00:22:05,500
you apply specific deformations to the grid, which you get are other species that do exist.

173
00:22:05,500 --> 00:22:09,500
Now, at the time, there was no molecular mechanism, of course, known.

174
00:22:09,500 --> 00:22:11,500
There was nothing really known about this.

175
00:22:11,500 --> 00:22:16,500
But I think now we can do some very interesting things with this idea.

176
00:22:16,500 --> 00:22:24,500
So navigating these spaces, changing your body shape to move from one region to another is not trivial

177
00:22:24,500 --> 00:22:28,500
because there may be local minima, there may be barriers, there may be all kinds of things.

178
00:22:28,500 --> 00:22:32,500
So that's the task that we face as morphogenetic agents.

179
00:22:32,500 --> 00:22:37,500
Now embryogenesis is very good at this. It's extremely reliable.

180
00:22:37,500 --> 00:22:43,500
So you start off as this kind of pattern, and eventually you end up here.

181
00:22:43,500 --> 00:22:47,500
And that's generally very low, very low error.

182
00:22:47,500 --> 00:22:55,500
But we can already see actually that this process is not simply a kind of pre-programmed hardwired walk in morphospace

183
00:22:55,500 --> 00:22:58,500
because we can deviate in the middle.

184
00:22:58,500 --> 00:23:03,500
So for example, we can take this nice human embryo, divide it in half, literally cut it in half,

185
00:23:03,500 --> 00:23:08,500
and what you get are not two half organisms, you get two perfectly normal monosygotic twins.

186
00:23:08,500 --> 00:23:09,500
This is where twins come from.

187
00:23:09,500 --> 00:23:18,500
And so this is a regenerative event where each half of this embryo basically realizes that it's actually not where it's supposed to be in morphospace

188
00:23:18,500 --> 00:23:24,500
and it needs to regenerate the other half in order to make the correct changes to get to its goal and where it needs to go.

189
00:23:24,500 --> 00:23:31,500
So this is not just embryonic, for example, back to this salamander, this axolotl.

190
00:23:31,500 --> 00:23:39,500
These guys regenerate their limbs, their eyes, their jaws, their spinal cords, portions of their heart and brain, their ovaries.

191
00:23:39,500 --> 00:23:41,500
They're incredibly regenerative as adults.

192
00:23:41,500 --> 00:23:46,500
And what happens is that you can amputate, for example, this limb at different positions.

193
00:23:46,500 --> 00:23:49,500
No matter where you cut, the cells will very quickly grow.

194
00:23:49,500 --> 00:23:53,500
They will grow exactly what's needed to make a normal axolotl limb, and then they stop.

195
00:23:53,500 --> 00:23:56,500
So this is a kind of example of anatomical homeostasis.

196
00:23:56,500 --> 00:24:02,500
They will continue working from wherever starting position until they get to where they're going.

197
00:24:02,500 --> 00:24:08,500
Parenthetically, this is not just for frogs and axolotls and worms.

198
00:24:08,500 --> 00:24:10,500
The human liver, of course, is regenerative.

199
00:24:10,500 --> 00:24:11,500
Even the ancient Greeks knew that.

200
00:24:11,500 --> 00:24:15,500
I have no idea how they knew that, but it seems like they did.

201
00:24:15,500 --> 00:24:21,500
Deer, every year, regenerate massive amounts of bone up to a centimeter and a half of new bone per day.

202
00:24:21,500 --> 00:24:24,500
Bone, vasculature, innervation, skin.

203
00:24:24,500 --> 00:24:28,500
And even human children below a certain age can regenerate their fingertips.

204
00:24:28,500 --> 00:24:32,500
If you just leave it alone, it will basically regrow cosmetically a very, very nice outcome.

205
00:24:32,500 --> 00:24:37,500
So we have some ability to improve our position in morphospace.

206
00:24:37,500 --> 00:24:45,500
One of the most amazing things about it is that as a body, as a living creature, you can't count on your environment.

207
00:24:45,500 --> 00:24:50,500
You can't count on, in other words, you can't count on the environment being the same as it was before.

208
00:24:50,500 --> 00:24:58,500
You can't count on not being perturbed during the developmental process, maybe physiologically, maybe metabolically, maybe with a parasite or a teratogen.

209
00:24:58,500 --> 00:24:59,500
So you can't count on that.

210
00:24:59,500 --> 00:25:01,500
And you still need to get your job done.

211
00:25:01,500 --> 00:25:05,500
In fact, you can't even count on your own parts being what you expected them to be.

212
00:25:05,500 --> 00:25:14,500
Now, of course, we don't have any machines that can do this, that can repair themselves after damage or put themselves together with diverse parts.

213
00:25:14,500 --> 00:25:17,500
This is one of my favorite examples of all time.

214
00:25:17,500 --> 00:25:22,500
This is a cross-section through a new kidney tubule.

215
00:25:22,500 --> 00:25:26,500
So here's the lumen of the tubule and these are the cells that make up the tubule.

216
00:25:26,500 --> 00:25:31,500
Normally, it's, let's say, around eight cells that work together to form this kind of tubule.

217
00:25:31,500 --> 00:25:39,500
One thing you can do is you can make these cells what's called polyploid, which means they have extra genetic material.

218
00:25:39,500 --> 00:25:50,500
Amazing thing number one, with the excess genetic material, you still get a perfectly normal, no problem that there are all kinds of extra information around, no problem.

219
00:25:50,500 --> 00:25:52,500
But what does happen is that the cells get much bigger.

220
00:25:52,500 --> 00:25:58,500
And as the cells get physically bigger, fewer of them are needed to make the exact same shape lumen.

221
00:25:58,500 --> 00:26:08,500
Now, that's amazing thing number two is that the number of these cells will actually scale to their correct size so that you get the same final outcome with different numbers of cells.

222
00:26:08,500 --> 00:26:19,500
But the most amazing thing is that when you make these cells absolutely gigantic so that only one cell is big enough to make the whole lumen, what it will do is it will no longer cooperate with other cells.

223
00:26:19,500 --> 00:26:25,500
One cell will bend around itself making the exact same lumen.

224
00:26:25,500 --> 00:26:28,500
Now, the incredible thing about that is this is a different molecular mechanism.

225
00:26:28,500 --> 00:26:30,500
This was cell-to-cell communication.

226
00:26:30,500 --> 00:26:32,500
This is cytoskeletal bending.

227
00:26:32,500 --> 00:26:46,500
So what happens is that this is a kind of top-down causation where in service of a large-scale anatomical spec, meaning having the correct lumen, you can call up different molecular mechanisms to get the job done.

228
00:26:46,500 --> 00:26:58,500
So this, again, is sticking with this theme of intelligence as the ability to handle novelty in terms of getting to where you're going from diverse starting positions with perturbations, both external and internal.

229
00:26:58,500 --> 00:27:00,500
You know, your own parts are changing.

230
00:27:00,500 --> 00:27:02,500
Can you still do what you need to do?

231
00:27:02,500 --> 00:27:05,500
And all of this is described in some of these papers.

232
00:27:05,500 --> 00:27:11,500
And then the final thing is that your walkthrough morphospace doesn't even have to be the same path.

233
00:27:11,500 --> 00:27:14,500
So here, for example, here's a frog.

234
00:27:14,500 --> 00:27:16,500
Frogs normally do not regenerate their legs.

235
00:27:16,500 --> 00:27:20,500
As I'll tell you momentarily, we have figured out a way to make them regenerate their legs.

236
00:27:20,500 --> 00:27:24,500
And when they do, so this is a pretty good frog leg regeneration.

237
00:27:24,500 --> 00:27:27,500
You can see here, it's got the toes, the toenails, the webbing.

238
00:27:27,500 --> 00:27:28,500
I mean, everything's good.

239
00:27:28,500 --> 00:27:36,500
But in fact, the way it got here is not at all how frogs normally regenerate their limbs, normally develop their limbs.

240
00:27:36,500 --> 00:27:38,500
So normal frog limb morphogenesis is here.

241
00:27:38,500 --> 00:27:43,500
You make these things and then you sort of make that, you kill off the cells in the middle to make the paddle.

242
00:27:43,500 --> 00:27:46,500
This grows in a completely different way.

243
00:27:46,500 --> 00:27:51,500
You've got the middle, this kind of middle stalk here with the toenail, and then the toes sort of come off to the side.

244
00:27:51,500 --> 00:27:52,500
It looks much more like a plant.

245
00:27:52,500 --> 00:27:57,500
So it takes a different path through morphospace, but it ends up in the same place.

246
00:27:57,500 --> 00:28:07,500
So all of this is back to illustrating some of these amazing abilities of the cells to navigate.

247
00:28:07,500 --> 00:28:14,500
And so one very canonical example of this that we discovered a few years ago is this.

248
00:28:14,500 --> 00:28:15,500
So here's a tadpole.

249
00:28:15,500 --> 00:28:18,500
Here's the gut, the brain, the nostrils, and the eyes here.

250
00:28:18,500 --> 00:28:20,500
This tadpole needs to become a frog.

251
00:28:20,500 --> 00:28:23,500
In order for a tadpole face to be a frog face, things have to move.

252
00:28:23,500 --> 00:28:27,500
So the jaws have to move, the eyes have to move forward, everything has to move.

253
00:28:27,500 --> 00:28:33,500
And it used to be thought that this process was hardwired because if you're a standard tadpole and you want to be a standard frog,

254
00:28:33,500 --> 00:28:38,500
all you have to remember is which direction and by how much every piece of the face moves.

255
00:28:38,500 --> 00:28:42,500
What we did, and we suspected that there was more intelligence to this process than that.

256
00:28:42,500 --> 00:28:44,500
And so we did an experiment.

257
00:28:44,500 --> 00:28:47,500
We created so-called Picasso frogs.

258
00:28:47,500 --> 00:28:50,500
And so these are tadpoles in which everything is messed up.

259
00:28:50,500 --> 00:28:55,500
The eyes on the side of the head, the jaws are off to the side and the nostrils are too far back.

260
00:28:55,500 --> 00:28:57,500
I mean, everything is in the wrong position.

261
00:28:57,500 --> 00:29:04,500
And we found that these animals still largely make pretty normal frogs because all of these pieces will move in novel paths.

262
00:29:04,500 --> 00:29:09,500
In fact, sometimes they go too far and have to double back to give you a normal frog face.

263
00:29:09,500 --> 00:29:14,500
So what the genetics gives you is not some hardwired system that always moves in the same way.

264
00:29:14,500 --> 00:29:20,500
What it specifies is a really interesting error minimization machine that however you start it off,

265
00:29:20,500 --> 00:29:26,500
obviously with some limits, will try to minimize the error and get to the correct final shape.

266
00:29:26,500 --> 00:29:29,500
If we had a robotic swarm, a collection of robots that was able to do this,

267
00:29:29,500 --> 00:29:32,500
we would call this a prize-winning example of collective intelligence,

268
00:29:32,500 --> 00:29:35,500
but we don't have such a technology yet.

269
00:29:35,500 --> 00:29:39,500
So we started trying to understand this process.

270
00:29:39,500 --> 00:29:41,500
How does all this work?

271
00:29:41,500 --> 00:29:49,500
To the standard feed-forward kind of open-loop process of developmental biology that you would read about in class,

272
00:29:49,500 --> 00:29:55,500
where there are genes, they make proteins, the proteins interact via some physics and chemistry,

273
00:29:55,500 --> 00:29:57,500
and then there's this emergent outcome.

274
00:29:57,500 --> 00:30:03,500
We add to this these feedback loops whereby this is actually a homeostatic system.

275
00:30:03,500 --> 00:30:13,500
If that anatomy is disrupted in some way by injury, by mutations, by teratogens, by parasites, whatever,

276
00:30:13,500 --> 00:30:16,500
then these feedback loops will kick in to try to minimize error.

277
00:30:16,500 --> 00:30:19,500
The cells will do what they can to try to get back to the correct shape.

278
00:30:19,500 --> 00:30:23,500
Think about your thermostat. It's a basic homeostatic circuit.

279
00:30:23,500 --> 00:30:27,500
Now, on the one hand, this is pretty expected.

280
00:30:27,500 --> 00:30:30,500
Biologists know all about feedback loops and so on.

281
00:30:30,500 --> 00:30:34,500
On the other hand, there are two kind of weird and unusual things here.

282
00:30:34,500 --> 00:30:38,500
The first is that every homeostatic process has to have a set point.

283
00:30:38,500 --> 00:30:45,500
So if you're going to try to get back to where you need to be, you have to remember where the right position is.

284
00:30:45,500 --> 00:30:47,500
You have to store a set point.

285
00:30:47,500 --> 00:30:52,500
We're used to thinking about scalars, single numbers as set points, so temperature, pH, things like that.

286
00:30:52,500 --> 00:30:57,500
But in this case, the set point is some sort of a large-scale geometry.

287
00:30:57,500 --> 00:31:01,500
It's a descriptor of some kind of coarse-grained descriptor of an anatomy.

288
00:31:01,500 --> 00:31:03,500
So it's a complex data structure.

289
00:31:03,500 --> 00:31:08,500
And in general, biologists don't love to think about goal-directed processes.

290
00:31:08,500 --> 00:31:13,500
The idea is there's supposed to be emergence and kind of emergent complexity.

291
00:31:13,500 --> 00:31:19,500
But this idea that things are working towards a goal the way that any navigational system fundamentally does

292
00:31:19,500 --> 00:31:24,500
is really not something that is very comfortable, certainly, for molecular biology.

293
00:31:24,500 --> 00:31:27,500
So how would something like this work?

294
00:31:27,500 --> 00:31:34,500
How could we have a navigating system that can have goals in anatomical space?

295
00:31:34,500 --> 00:31:37,500
And so here's where we start to think about bioelectricity,

296
00:31:37,500 --> 00:31:45,500
because our best example of a mechanism that allows us to navigate space towards goals is the brain.

297
00:31:45,500 --> 00:31:48,500
And in the brain, we know roughly what the architecture looks like.

298
00:31:48,500 --> 00:31:52,500
There are cells that communicate with other cells and networks.

299
00:31:52,500 --> 00:31:54,500
These cells have ion channels.

300
00:31:54,500 --> 00:31:58,500
So these are little proteins that help set a voltage to the cell.

301
00:31:58,500 --> 00:32:02,500
And that voltage may or may not be communicated to its neighbors through these little gap junctions.

302
00:32:02,500 --> 00:32:08,500
These are like electrical synapses that allow electrical information to pass back and forth.

303
00:32:08,500 --> 00:32:10,500
And so that's the hardware of the brain.

304
00:32:10,500 --> 00:32:15,500
And what that hardware enables is a kind of software that, among other things, navigates spaces.

305
00:32:15,500 --> 00:32:17,500
So here's a zebrafish.

306
00:32:17,500 --> 00:32:24,500
This is a movie taken by this group here that shows all the electrical activity in the living zebrafish brain.

307
00:32:24,500 --> 00:32:30,500
And so the commitment of neuroscience is that if we understood how to decode this information,

308
00:32:30,500 --> 00:32:36,500
we would be able to know what the cognitive content of this brain was.

309
00:32:36,500 --> 00:32:42,500
So the memories, the preferences, the goals, whatever else the system was going to do, we should be able to decode it.

310
00:32:42,500 --> 00:32:45,500
So this is that cycle that's called neural decoding.

311
00:32:45,500 --> 00:32:49,500
We should be able to understand what all these patterns mean.

312
00:32:49,500 --> 00:32:53,500
Well, it turns out that this is not just for brains.

313
00:32:53,500 --> 00:32:55,500
This is an extremely ancient system.

314
00:32:55,500 --> 00:32:57,500
All the cells in your body have ion channels.

315
00:32:57,500 --> 00:33:00,500
Most cells have gap junctions with each other.

316
00:33:00,500 --> 00:33:02,500
And what we might be able to do is just like neuroscientists,

317
00:33:02,500 --> 00:33:05,500
we might be able to extend this whole scheme to ask,

318
00:33:05,500 --> 00:33:08,500
what are your tissues thinking about at any point in time?

319
00:33:08,500 --> 00:33:10,500
Specifically, to read the electrical.

320
00:33:10,500 --> 00:33:13,500
So this is a time lapse of an early frog embryo.

321
00:33:13,500 --> 00:33:16,500
The colors are a fluorescent dye reporting voltage,

322
00:33:16,500 --> 00:33:21,500
the same way that we did here that was done here with these zebrafish.

323
00:33:21,500 --> 00:33:25,500
And we might be able to decode this information to ask,

324
00:33:25,500 --> 00:33:28,500
what are the targets in anatomical amorphous space?

325
00:33:28,500 --> 00:33:30,500
What is this thing going to build?

326
00:33:30,500 --> 00:33:35,500
And so there's this amazing isomorphism between the story of the brain,

327
00:33:35,500 --> 00:33:40,500
where you've got the hardware and the software and there's various experiences

328
00:33:40,500 --> 00:33:43,500
and various other ways that this software gets modified.

329
00:33:43,500 --> 00:33:47,500
The hardware basically, it just gets built in development.

330
00:33:47,500 --> 00:33:53,500
And what the brain does is it controls muscles to move your body in three-dimensional space.

331
00:33:53,500 --> 00:33:56,500
Now, that's a pretty cool trick. Where did it learn this trick?

332
00:33:56,500 --> 00:34:00,500
Well, evolutionarily, this is exactly the same as something that was going on

333
00:34:00,500 --> 00:34:04,500
long before brains appeared, which is this exact same system,

334
00:34:04,500 --> 00:34:09,500
but it used to be for moving the body configuration in amorphous space.

335
00:34:09,500 --> 00:34:11,500
Before there were nerves and muscles,

336
00:34:11,500 --> 00:34:17,500
cells needed to talk to each other and process information to get around in amorphous space.

337
00:34:17,500 --> 00:34:24,500
And so we've argued in this paper that basically neural electricity

338
00:34:24,500 --> 00:34:29,500
is just an evolutionary pivot across spaces from amorphous space to three-dimensional space

339
00:34:29,500 --> 00:34:35,500
of a very ancient system for processing information long before brains arose.

340
00:34:35,500 --> 00:34:39,500
So in my group, we were thinking about this and we asked this question,

341
00:34:39,500 --> 00:34:46,500
okay, if that's how it works, could we make some tools to read and write this electrical information

342
00:34:46,500 --> 00:34:51,500
and to really understand how it's navigating that shape-change space?

343
00:34:51,500 --> 00:34:58,500
So we developed some of the first tools to read and write information into non-brain tissues.

344
00:34:58,500 --> 00:35:02,500
So of course, these dyes, so these are voltage-sensitive fluorescent dyes

345
00:35:02,500 --> 00:35:07,500
that report all the electrical conversations that these cells are having with each other.

346
00:35:07,500 --> 00:35:11,500
So here's a time-lapse of these cells figuring out who's going to be left, right, dorsal, ventral.

347
00:35:11,500 --> 00:35:15,500
So all of this is, you're looking at these cells having those conversations.

348
00:35:15,500 --> 00:35:20,500
We do a lot of computational modeling to ask, okay, given where the ions are going,

349
00:35:20,500 --> 00:35:22,500
how can we predict these voltages?

350
00:35:22,500 --> 00:35:24,500
I'm going to show you two patterns.

351
00:35:24,500 --> 00:35:28,500
Here's a time-lapse. It happens to be grayscale, but it's the exact same idea.

352
00:35:28,500 --> 00:35:32,500
Here's a time-lapse of a frog embryo putting its face together.

353
00:35:32,500 --> 00:35:35,500
And what you will see, and this is one frame out of that video,

354
00:35:35,500 --> 00:35:40,500
what you will see is that this is something we call the electric face discovered by my colleague, Danny Adams.

355
00:35:40,500 --> 00:35:49,500
When she was in my group doing this profiling, she found that, here's a particular frame from that video

356
00:35:49,500 --> 00:35:53,500
where you can see the animal's right eye, the mouth, the placodes.

357
00:35:53,500 --> 00:35:59,500
All of this is already demarcated before the genes start to come on and really pattern the face.

358
00:35:59,500 --> 00:36:03,500
This is a bioelectric pre-pattern of what the future face is going to look like.

359
00:36:03,500 --> 00:36:05,500
And I'm showing you this one because it's so simple.

360
00:36:05,500 --> 00:36:07,500
It literally looks like a face, right?

361
00:36:07,500 --> 00:36:11,500
There are other patterns that are much more complex that you can't really just sort of visually decode.

362
00:36:11,500 --> 00:36:13,500
But this one is very clear.

363
00:36:13,500 --> 00:36:16,500
This is the memory of what a tadpole face is going to look like.

364
00:36:16,500 --> 00:36:20,500
And if you move this, if you disrupt this electrical pattern,

365
00:36:20,500 --> 00:36:24,500
the gene expression will change and the organogenesis will change.

366
00:36:24,500 --> 00:36:28,500
And I'll show you examples of that momentarily.

367
00:36:28,500 --> 00:36:34,500
So this is an endogenous pattern that is required for normal development.

368
00:36:34,500 --> 00:36:39,500
In fact, human channelopathies of the human patients that have craniofacial defects

369
00:36:39,500 --> 00:36:43,500
often have mutations in ion channels that screw up this pattern.

370
00:36:43,500 --> 00:36:44,500
So that's a normal pattern.

371
00:36:44,500 --> 00:36:46,500
Here's a pathological pattern.

372
00:36:46,500 --> 00:36:48,500
We've put in a human oncogene.

373
00:36:48,500 --> 00:36:50,500
These cells will make a tumor.

374
00:36:50,500 --> 00:36:52,500
But even before the tumor becomes apparent,

